@Node Usage "Usage"

 Usage
 =====
 QuickNS STRING/A,NODELIST/K/M,FULL/S,SMALL/S,CITY/S,SYSOP/S,NODENR/S,
         DEFZONE/K/N,ZONE/K,REGION/K,NET/K,HUB/K

 STRING       This is the string that you want to search for. No wildcards
              are allowed.

 NODELIST     Here you can enter the nodelists you want to search. You can
              enter several nodelists and you can use wildcards. QuickNS
              also supports pointlist in the TrapList format.

 FULL/SMALL   QuickNS can show its output in two ways. FULL shows all
              information and needs three lines, SMALL shows the most
              important things on one line.

 CITY/SYSOP   With these switches, you can decide if QuickNS should show
              the city or sysop name in SMALL mode.

 NODENR       If this switch is set, QuickNS also searches for the string
              in the node numbers. You can for example search for "/0.0"
              to get all region and net coordinators. This is automatically
              enabled if the search string contains ":", "/" or ".".
              Unfortunately, searching node numbers makes QuickNS almost
              twice as slow.

 DEFZONE      This option sets the default Zone for regional nodelists
              with no Zone line. (Defaults to 2)

 ZONE/REGION  Use these if you only want to search part of the nodelist.
 NET/HUB      "ZONE 2" searches in zone 2, "HUB 2:200/200" searches the
              nodes under the hub 2:200/200 etc.

 READ THIS! Don't be confused if QuickNS shows a node in SMALL mode and
 you have no idea why it showed it. The program searches the whole line
 in the nodelist, so it might have found the string in the flags or
 something like that.

 Environment variable
 ====================
 You can of course also set the default options for QuickNS using the
 environment variable QUICKNS_OPTS. Here you may use all switches you can
 use on command line except for STRING. For example, I have my
 QUICKNS_OPTS set to this:

 NODELIST:(NODELIST|POINTSWE|AMYLIST).[0-9]?? FULL

 (I am using "[0-9]??" instead of "#?" to make sure that QuickNS doesn't
 search compressed nodelists or similar)

 Converting nodelists
 ====================
 A couple of years ago, I wrote a program called NLConvert that converted
 a FidoNet nodelist to a readable text file. That program isn't needed
 anymore, as QuickNS does the job better and even faster! With QuickNS,
 you can convert just part of the nodelist and have more control of the
 output.

 Example:

 QuickNS >Nodelist:Nodelist.txt "" SMALL NODELIST Nodelist:Nodelist.[0-9]??

 Examples
 ========
 Here are a few examples to make you understand how QuickNS works:

 QuickNS /42.0 ZONE 2
    Searches Zone 2 for nodes with the node number 42.

 QuickNS /0.0
    Lists all net, zone and region coordinators in all zones

 QuickNS "" HUB 2:200/200
    Lists all nodes under Hub 2:200/200

 QuickNS billing Zone 1 Small
    Searches for nodes with the string "billing" in zone 1 and lists them
    one on each line.

 (The examples assume that you have set your default nodelist(s) using
  the QUICKNS_OPTS environment variable)

@EndNode

@Node Future "Future of QuickNS"

 Future of QuickNS
 =================
 I would of course like to speed up QuickNS a bit more. I can currently
 think of two ways of doing it:

 1) Downcode the whole program to assembler. That is a lot of work, and I'm
    not sure if the speed improvement would be worth it.

 b) Use asynchronous I/O. Unfortunately I don't know how to do this, so
    if you could send me some source, I would be grateful.

@EndNode

